title: Ford Will Build 4 Factories in a Big Electric Vehicle Push
content: The automaker and a supplier will spend $11.4 billion on three battery factories and a truck plant, creating 11,000 jobs.

title: Power Outages Hit China, Threatening the Economy and Christmas
content: High demand and soaring energy prices have forced some factories to shut down, adding further problems for already snarled global supply chains.

title: Wall Street Scans the Lots as Used Cars Prod Inflation
content: The Manheim Used Vehicle Value Index, an obscure tracker of wholesale used-car prices, has become closely watched by the finance world’s high rollers.

title: Fed Officials Under Fire for 2020 Securities Trading Will Resign
content: Robert S. Kaplan will exit his role as head of the Federal Reserve Bank of Dallas next month. Eric S. Rosengren, the head of the Federal Reserve Bank of Boston, is also retiring earlier than planned.

title: Goldman Sachs, Ozy Media and a $40 Million Conference Call Gone Wrong
content: The digital media company has raised eyebrows for its claims about its audience size for years. Then came the strange voice on the phone.

title: Scotland’s Oil Industry Is Fading as Wind Energy Beckons
content: Oil and gas production in the North Sea is not the economic juggernaut it once was. Can floating wind turbines offer an alternative?

title: New Limits Give Chinese Video Gamers Whiplash
content: China has a complex relationship with video games. New government rules for minors have made it even more so.

title: How China Plans to Avert an Evergrande Financial Crisis
content: Control of the banking system gives Beijing the tools to stop a broader collapse, officials believe, while censorship and police powers can stifle protests.

title: Yellen and Powell warn that the Delta variant is slowing the recovery.
content: The Treasury secretary and the Federal Reserve chair prepared remarks ahead of their testimony today to the Senate Banking Committee.

title: How Covid Misinformation Created a Run on Animal Medicine
content: Veterinarians, ranchers and farmers say they are struggling with the effects of the surging demand for ivermectin, a deworming drug.

title: Facebook groups promoting ivermectin as a Covid-19 treatment continue to flourish.
content: In some of the groups, members are given advice on how to evade the company’s rules on misinformation.

title: SoCal Gas agrees to pay up to $1.8 billion to settle claims from nation’s biggest gas leak.
content: The natural gas leak, in 2015, forced thousands of people from their homes in an area of Los Angeles.

title: Activision to pay $18 million settlement over workplace misconduct.
content: The complaint by a federal agency followed several other legal actions taken against the game maker, which has been accused of sexual harassment and discrimination.

title: Top Fed officials say the labor market needs more time to heal.
content: Lael Brainard, a Federal Reserve governor, argued that the job market was not tight, and John C. Williams, the president of the New York Fed, said it had “a long way to go.”

title: Creative Artists Deal for ICM Is Set to Reshape Hollywood’s Talent Business
content: The sum was not disclosed, but the merger of two rival agencies is the industry’s largest in a decade.

title: Explaining the U.S. Debt Limit and Why It Became a Bargaining Tool
content: Political polarization turned a tool for fiscal responsibility into a recipe for economic calamity.

title: A Strange Voice on the Phone
content: The digital media company Ozy was close to securing a $40 investment from Goldman Sachs before things got weird.

title: ‘Every Day Is Frightening’: Working for the Top U.S. Employer Amid Covid
content: As offices debate the merits and logistics of reopening, a parallel sphere of workers like Peter Naughton, a Walmart cashier, seem to inhabit another world. Often their jobs just got really hard.

title: Finding Memories, and Mom’s Sewing Stuff, in a Reused Cookie Tin
content: The containers we use over and over, from Cool Whip tubs to Taster’s Choice jars, can evoke stronger feelings than the food that came in them.

title: The Economy Looks Solid. But These Are the Big Risks Ahead.
content: One concern is that political leaders will mismanage things in the world’s largest and second-largest economies.

title: America’s Need to Pay Its Bills Has Spawned a Political Game
content: Republicans and Democrats have long sparred over raising the debt ceiling. But this time, the odds are growing that the U.S. could default.

title: The Week in Business: A Debt Deadline Looms
content: The Fed indicated it was planning to slow down its purchases of government bonds as soon as November. And food delivery workers in New York gained protections.

title: This Lab Charges $380 for a Covid Test. Is That What Congress Had in Mind?
content: Insurers say it’s price-gouging, but a law left an opening for some labs to charge any price they wished.

title: A 3-D Model Built With Public Records and Phone Calls
content: For an interactive article on business inside the Empire State Building, a New York Times team turned to interviews with tenants, vacancy listings, promotional materials and real estate data.

title: How Record Rain and Officials’ Mistakes Led to Drownings on a Subway
content: The deluge in the city of Zhengzhou revealed how China’s years of go-go construction had left its cities vulnerable to climate change.

title: One Solution to a Shortage of Skilled Workers? Diversify the Construction Industry.
content: President Biden’s infrastructure plan would create a hiring challenge, but also an opportunity to recruit from communities that the industry has long ignored.

title: Long Hours, Low Pay, Loneliness and a Booming Industry
content: The ranks of home health aides are expected to grow more than any other job in the next decade. What kind of work are they being asked to do?

title: A Path to Financial Security That Doesn’t Lead to a 401(k)
content: Some Black and Hispanic millennials are looking to alternatives like real estate or entrepreneurship, or to trading stock on their own.

title: Want a Can’t Miss Productivity Tip? Forget About Being Productive.
content: People and industries measure how productive they are in similar ways. This extended period of remote work for many has revealed how flawed that can be.

title: Robinhood Hits Campus, Where Credit Card Companies Fear to Tread
content: The company plans to hit up college coffee shops to spread the word about its services. When credit card companies did it a generation ago, Congress got involved.

title: The Surveillance Apparatus That Surrounded Britney Spears
content: An account by a former employee of the security team hired by Ms. Spears’s father created the most detailed portrait yet of the singer’s life under 13 years of conservatorship.

title: U.S. Agrees to Release Huawei Executive in Case That Strained Ties With China
content: China reciprocated within hours, freeing two Canadians, a notable resolution in a relationship that has been spiraling downward.

title: Cliff Freeman, Adman Who Asked, ‘Where’s the Beef?,’ Dies at 80
content: His humorous touch was evident in commercials for Wendy’s, Little Caesars, Fox Sports and many other clients. “We have to win with wit,” he once said.
